{{About|the Parade Grounds on Alcatraz Island|military parade grounds|military parade}}
[[File:Alcatraz, 2010.jpg|thumb|right|The Parade Grounds is the flat area at the bottom of the cliff which contains [[Alcatraz Island Light]]]]
The '''Parade Grounds''' is a large concrete open area on the south end of  [[Alcatraz Island]], off the coast of [[San Francisco]], USA. They lie beyond [[Building 64]]. They were originally built in the 1860s on a barren site by the U.S. military who used the site for military drills and parades.<ref name="Jr.2012">{{cite book|last=Jr.|first=Jerry Lewis Champion|title=Alcatraz Unchained|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VQV5wM6qj1oC&pg=PA33|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=26 April 2012|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-4685-8753-1|page=33}}</ref>

After the island became a Federal Penitentiary in 1934, the Parade Grounds was used as a playground, especially on weekends and holidays, and was used host special events, often organized by the [[Social Hall (Alcatraz)|Officer's Club]].<ref name="Albright2008">{{cite book|last=Albright|first=Jim|title=Last Guard Out: A Riveting Account by the Last Guard to Leave Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fmVGYLGkLl4C&pg=PA192|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=30 March 2008|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-4343-5077-0|page=192}}</ref> As the nearby Building 64 aged and fell into disrepair, the operators of the prison funded several new residential blocks on the square.<ref name="Dunbar1999">{{cite book|last=Dunbar|first=Richard|title=Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OoXM5O9glN8C&pg=PA71|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=1 January 1999|publisher=Casa Editrice Bonechi|isbn=978-88-8029-940-0|page=71}}</ref> Gardens were developed around them, and handball and weightlifting facilities developed for the employees and their families.<ref name="Jim8">{{cite book|last=Albright|first=Jim|title=Last Guard Out: A Riveting Account by the Last Guard to Leave Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fmVGYLGkLl4C&pg=PA8|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=30 March 2008|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-4343-5077-0|page=8}}</ref> The children living in the quarters on the Parade Ground were known to other children and their families on Alcatraz as "the topside kids" because they lived above those residing in Building 64 on the dock below.<ref name="Wellman2008">{{cite book|last=Wellman|first=Gregory L.|title=A History of Alcatraz Island:: 1853-2008|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1duAUPaHSgcC&pg=PA93|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=28 May 2008|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-0-7385-5815-8|page=93}}</ref>

The island ceased use as a jail in 1963 and the residential buildings and gardens which were added were razed to the ground by the [[General Services Administration]] in the 1970s, but the foundation marks can still be seen.<ref name="Jim8"/>

[[File:Map of Alcatraz.png|600px|center|thumb|The Heliport and surrounding marked area is the Parade Grounds]]

