==Reboot==
{{main|The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle (TV series)}}

On April 12, 2018, it was announced that a reboot of the series from [[DreamWorks Animation]] would premiere on [[Amazon Prime Video]] on May 11, 2018. The series will be executive produced by [[Scott Fellows]] and [[Tiffany Ward]] (the daughter of Jay). The cast will include [[Tara Strong]] as Rocky, [[Brad Norman]] as Bullwinkle, [[Ben Diskin]] as Boris, [[Rachel Butera]] as Natasha, [[Piotr Michael]] as Fearless Leader, and [[Daran Norris]] as the Narrator.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cartoonbrew.com/internet-television/trailer-new-dreamworks-version-of-the-adventures-of-rocky-and-bullwinkle-157790.html|title=TRAILER: New Dreamworks Version Of 'The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle'|first=Amid|last=Amidi|work=Cartoon Brew|date=April 12, 2018|accessdate=April 12, 2018}}</ref>

== In other media ==

=== Advertising ===
* In 1966, the duo appeared between show segments in ads for [[General Mills]]' Frosty O's cereal<ref>{{cite web|title=Frosty O's Cereal Commercial 1966|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rNnIIqTxjZE|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=November 27, 2014|date=March 15, 2010}}</ref> and Kendall "Curad Comic Strips" plastic bandages<ref>{{cite web|title=Bullwinkle Bandaids 1966 TV Commercial|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pJHb_FjYqxc|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=November 27, 2014|date=March 15, 2010}}</ref>
* In the 1960s or 70s Rocky and Bullwinkle appeared in some U.S. [[postage stamp]]s with their friends.<ref name="Los Angeles Times">{{cite news|last1=Michaud|first1=Anne|title=Taco Bell Signs Up Rocky and Bullwinkle for Commercials|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-03-26/business/fi-15530_1_taco-bell|accessdate=July 25, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 26, 1993}}</ref>
* Rocky and Bullwinkle were in a 1986 ad for [[Hershey's Kisses]] snack pack.<ref name="Los Angeles Times" />
* In the 1990s Rocky and Bullwinkle appeared in some ads for [[Taco Bell]], wherein they ate real tacos by stopping Boris and Natasha from selling burgers.<ref name="Los Angeles Times" />
* [[DreamWorks Animation]] CGI versions of Rocky and Bullwinkle appeared in a 2014 [[GEICO advertising campaigns|advertisement]] for [[GEICO]], appearing with the [[GEICO Gecko]] in the [[Rocky Mountains]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Amidi|first1=Amid|title=Rocky & Bullwinkle Meet the GEICO Gecko|url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/advertising/rocky-bullwinkle-meet-the-geico-gecko-100231.html|publisher=[[Cartoon Brew]]|accessdate=June 30, 2014|date=June 6, 2014}}</ref>

=== Children's opera ===
* In 1997, The [[Los Angeles Opera]] toured a children's production, named ''Les Moose: The Operatic Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle'', around various L.A. County Elementary Schools. The story followed Boris and Natasha as they tried to steal the formula for Mooseberry Rocket Fuel from Bullwinkle J. Moose.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kids Tune In to Rocky, Bullwinkle--and Opera|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997/nov/22/local/me-56364|accessdate=October 1, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=November 22, 1997}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Warrick|first1=Pamela|title=A 'Rocky' Road to Opera|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/mar/09/news/cl-15305|accessdate=October 1, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 9, 1999}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=L. Kaplan|first1=Janice|title=The Opera Ain't Over Till the Big Moose Sings|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2000/01/14/the-opera-aint-over-till-the-big-moose-sings/5d4ddb9e-711a-409e-83dc-f910f57b53e4/|accessdate=October 1, 2017|work=The Washington Post|date=January 14, 2000}}</ref>

=== Comics ===
* A syndicated daily newspaper comic strip titled ''Bullwinkle'' began on July 23, 1962, with original stories drawn by [[Al Kilgore]]. It was syndicated by the [[Bell Syndicate]] and ended in 1965.<ref>"1962 Timeline: July 23. A Bullwinkle newspaper strip by Al Kilgore, based on the animated series, makes its debut." ''American Comic Book Chronicles: 1960–64'' by John Wells. TwoMorrows Publishing, 2012, Page 77.</ref>
*Rocky and Bullwinkle stories were published in [[Four Color]]
* Rocky and Bullwinkle comic books were published by [[Dell Comics]], [[Gold Key Comics]], [[Charlton Comics]] and [[Star Comics]] (an imprint of [[Marvel Comics]]). All were called ''Bullwinkle and Rocky''. The comics, although for children, did contain numerous references spoofing issues such as celebrity worship or the politics of the 1980s. In one Star Comics issue, Bullwinkle owns a small company, which makes him eligible to compete in a fun run in Washington DC for presidents of small companies. When Bullwinkle says he is there for the race, it is mistaken that he is campaigning for President. The comic also spoofed US President [[Ronald Reagan]], and he personally thanks Bullwinkle for stopping Boris & Natasha by rewarding him with monogrammed [[jelly bean]]s. Another comic broke the fourth wall when the narrator is outraged at a plot of Boris', to which Boris claims he has control of everyone "by capturing the Marvel Comics building and tying up the editor". When the narrator comments on how this is morally wrong, Boris quiets him by saying, "You will agree or you will not find paycheck in mail this month!" The same issue made reference to the [[1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Olympics]], which Boris had engineering in [[Fort Knox, Kentucky]] in an attempt to steal its gold by carving all the bars into gold medals, as well as furnishing false information to every country so Pottsylvania would win all the gold medals (and thus take all true gold) by virtue of default. After Boris is foiled, the narrator comments that the games will go on as planned in real time in [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]].
* From 2013 to 2014 [[IDW Publishing]] with [[DreamWorks Classics]] and Bullwinkle Studios released comics of ''Rocky and Bullwinkle'', ''Dudley Do-Right'' and ''Peabody and Sherman''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Guerrero|first=Tony|title=C2E2 13: Rocky & Bullwinkle, Mr. Peabody & Sherman and More Return to Comics|url=http://www.comicvine.com/articles/c2e2-13-rocky-bullwinkle-mr-peabody-sherman-and-mo/1100-146469/|accessdate=May 7, 2013|newspaper=Comic Vine|date=April 28, 2013}}</ref>
* Since 2017, [[American Mythology Productions]] took over the comic book license for Rocky and Bullwinkle.<ref>https://www.americanmythology.net/product-page/rocky-bullwinkle-show-1-greenawalt-classic-cvr-pre-order</ref>

=== Films ===
* ''[[Boris and Natasha: The Movie]]'' (1992), is a live-action [[feature film]] starring the two spies. Neither Rocky nor Bullwinkle appears in this film; however the characters of Toots and Harve are identified as "Moose" and "Squirrel" at one point in the film. The film was originally intended for theatrical release, but was premiered on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]].
* ''[[Dudley Do-Right (film)|Dudley Do-Right]]'' (1999), a theatrical live-action film, starred [[Brendan Fraser]], [[Sarah Jessica Parker]] and [[Alfred Molina]].
* ''[[The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle]]'' (2000) is a theatrical film starring Rocky and Bullwinkle. It was a mix of live-action with Rocky and Bullwinkle appearing as [[Computer animation|computer animated cartoon characters]] created by [[Industrial Light & Magic]]. June Foray returned to voice Rocky, while Bullwinkle was voiced by [[Keith Scott (voice actor)|Keith Scott]]. [[Robert De Niro]], [[Jason Alexander]] and [[Rene Russo]] played the live-action versions of Fearless Leader, Boris and Natasha, respectively. This film takes place 35 years after the show's cancellation.
* ''[[Mr. Peabody & Sherman]]'' is a 2014 animated film based off the two characters of the same name from the original cartoon.<ref>[[Mr. Peabody & Sherman]]</ref>
* ''[[Rocky & Bullwinkle (2014 film)|Rocky and Bullwinkle]]'' is a short animated film produced by [[DreamWorks Animation]], and directed by [[Gary Trousdale]]. It was originally planned to theatrically accompany the DreamWorks' feature film, ''Mr. Peabody & Sherman'',<ref name=TAGInterview3>{{cite news|last=Hulett|first=Steve|title=The Gary Trousdale Interview -- Part III|url=http://animationguildblog.blogspot.com/2012/10/the-gary-trousdale-interview-part-iii.html|accessdate=October 26, 2012|newspaper=The Animation Guild|date=October 26, 2012}}</ref> but was instead released on the [[Blu-ray Disc#Blu-ray 3D|Blu-ray 3D]] release of the film.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Truitt|first1=Brian|title=Go WABAC this fall with 'Mr. Peabody' on Blu-ray|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2014/06/19/mr-peabody-and-sherman-blu-ray-exclusive-clip/10830973/|accessdate=June 25, 2014|work=USA Today|date=June 19, 2014|quote=In addition, those who snag the 3-D Blu-ray version will enjoy a new animated adventure with Rocky and Bullwinkle.}}</ref> The short features June Foray as Rocky<ref>{{cite news|last=Wolfe|first=Jennifer|title=DreamWorks Animation Previews 2013 Slate|url=http://www.awn.com/news/cg/dreamworks-animation-previews-2013-slate|accessdate=October 20, 2013|newspaper=Animation World Network|date=December 6, 2012}}</ref> and [[Tom Kenny]] as Bullwinkle.<ref>{{cite news|last=VanDerWerff|first=Todd|title=SpongeBob's Tom Kenny talks his favorite voiceover artists|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/spongebobs-tom-kenny-talks-his-favorite-voiceover,104133/2/|accessdate=October 20, 2013|newspaper=A.V. Club|date=October 14, 2013}}</ref>

=== Music recordings ===
* Golden Records released a phonograph album of songs, ''Rocky the Flying Squirrel & His Friends'' (1961), using [[voice actor]]s from the series. Boris and Natasha, for example, sing: "We will double, single and triple cross our very closest friends!"
* A 78rpm single (Golden 659) was released on yellow vinyl. This had Rocky singing "I Was Born To Be Airborne" on one side, backed with Bullwinkle singing "I'm Rocky's Pal". The single sold in grocery stores. Paul Parnes (who later wrote songs for ''[[Sesame Street]]'') is credited as composer. "Some nutty characters get together here for the benefit of the very young. Lots of laughs for the juvenile sense of humor."<ref>{{cite news|work=Billboard| page= 78|date= September 18, 1961|title=Interview with composer Paul Parnes}}</ref>
* The pseudonymously-named Boris Badenough released a record called "Hey Rocky!" on Trax Records in 1986. The record featured a house-music beat underneath clips from the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Boris-Badenough-Hey-Rocky/release/31299|title=Boris Badenough – Hey Rocky!|website=Discogs}}</ref>
* In 2007, [[Blackstone Audio]] released the audio tracks of 15 of the ''Fractured Fairy Tales'' on CD.<ref>{{cite book|publisher=Blackstone Audio|title=Fractured Fairy Tales|author=Ward, Jay|date=2007|isbn= 978-1-4332-0162-2}}</ref>

=== Toys ===
* In 1999, [[Mattel]] released a numbered collector series under its [[Hot Wheels]] toy line, the "Car-Toon Friends" series. It contained 4 cars; the now-retired model "XT-3" for Rocky, "Double Vision" for Bullwinkle, "Saltflat Racer" for Natasha and "Lakestar" for Boris. They are no longer produced with these paint jobs and, as of December 2012, are hard to find.{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}

=== Video games ===
* [[THQ]] released ''[[The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle and Friends (video game)|The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle and Friends]]'' for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]], [[Game Boy]], and [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]] in 1992. [[Absolute Entertainment]] also released a version for the [[Sega Genesis]], in 1993.
* A trivia game, titled ''Rocky & Bullwinkle's Know-It-All Quiz Game'', was released for Windows 95/98 and Mac (for PC), in 1998.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Foran|first1=Katherine|title=Trivia Game Sadly Miscasts Ditsy Duo|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-12-03/features/9812030358_1_rocky-and-bullwinkle-trivia-game-educational-trivia|accessdate=December 5, 2015|work=Chicago Tribune|date=December 3, 1998}}</ref>
* [[Zen Studios]] released an [[Xbox Live Arcade]] video game titled ''[[Rocky and Bullwinkle (video game)|Rocky and Bullwinkle]]'' for download on April 16, 2008.<ref>{{cite web | last =  | title = But That Trick Never Works: The Bullwinkle Show Coming This Holiday Season | work = XBLArcade.com | date = November 16, 2007 | url = http://www.xblarcade.com/node/1424 | doi =  | accessdate = 2007-11-16 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071214100608/http://www.xblarcade.com/node/1424 | archivedate = December 14, 2007 | df =  }}</ref>
* [[Data East]] released a pinball in 1993.<ref>url = http://www.ipdb.org/machine.cgi?id=23</ref>

