{{infobox biodatabase |title = Uberon |logo =[[File:Database.png]] |description = Uberon, an integrative multi-species anatomy ontology. |scope = Anatomical Structures |organism = [[Metazoa]] |center = |laboratory = |author = |citation = Mungall & al. (2012)<ref name="pmid22293552"/> |released = 2012 |standard = |format = [[Web Ontology Language|OWL]] and OBO |url = http://uberon.org |download = http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/uberon/merged.owl |webservice = |sql = |sparql = http://sparql.hegroup.org/sparql |webapp = |standalone = |license = open |versioning = |frequency = |curation = |bookmark = |version= }}
'''Uberon''' is a [[comparative anatomy]] [[Ontology (information science)|ontology]] representing a variety of structures found in [[metazoa|animals]], such as [[lungs]], [[muscles]], [[bone]]s, [[feathers]] and [[Fish_anatomy#Fins|fins]]. These structures are connected to other structures via relationships such as [[part-of]] and develops-from.<ref name="pmid22293552">{{cite journal |last=Mungall|first=Christopher J|authorlink=|author2=Torniai Carlo |author3=Gkoutos Georgios V |author4=Lewis Suzanna E |author5=Haendel Melissa A |year=2012|title=Uberon, an integrative multi-species anatomy ontology|journal = Genome Biol.|volume=13|issue=1|pages=R5|publisher= |location = England| issn = | pmid = 22293552|doi = 10.1186/gb-2012-13-1-r5| bibcode = | oclc =| id = | url = | pmc =3334586 | format = | accessdate = | laysummary = | laysource = | laydate = | quote = }}</ref> One of the uses of this ontology is to integrate data from different [[biological databases]], and other species-specific ontologies such as the [[Foundational Model of Anatomy]].<ref name="pmid19956802">{{Cite journal | last1 = Washington | first1 = N. L. | last2 = Haendel | first2 = M. A. | last3 = Mungall | first3 = C. J. | last4 = Ashburner | first4 = M. | last5 = Westerfield | first5 = M. | last6 = Lewis | first6 = S. E. | editor1-last = Buetow | editor1-first = Kenneth H | title = Linking Human Diseases to Animal Models Using Ontology-Based Phenotype Annotation | doi = 10.1371/journal.pbio.1000247 | journal = PLoS Biology | volume = 7 | issue = 11 | pages = e1000247 | year = 2009 | pmid = 19956802 | pmc =2774506 }}</ref><ref name="pmid21737429">{{Cite journal | last1 = Hoehndorf | first1 = R. | last2 = Schofield | first2 = P. N. | last3 = Gkoutos | first3 = G. V. | doi = 10.1093/nar/gkr538 | title = PhenomeNET: A whole-phenome approach to disease gene discovery | journal = Nucleic Acids Research | volume = 39 | issue = 18 | pages = e119 | year = 2011 | pmid = 21737429 | pmc =3185433 }}</ref><ref name="pmid22331800">{{Cite journal | last1 = Chen | first1 = C. K. | last2 = Mungall | first2 = C. J. | last3 = Gkoutos | first3 = G. V. | last4 = Doelken | first4 = S. C. | last5 = Köhler | first5 = S. | last6 = Ruef | first6 = B. J. | last7 = Smith | first7 = C. | last8 = Westerfield | first8 = M. | last9 = Robinson | first9 = P. N. | last10 = Lewis | doi = 10.1002/humu.22051 | first10 = S. E. | last11 = Schofield | first11 = P. N. | last12 = Smedley | first12 = D. | title = MouseFinder: Candidate disease genes from mouse phenotype data | journal = Human Mutation | volume = 33 | issue = 5 | pages = 858–866 | year = 2012 | pmid = 22331800 | pmc =3327758 }}</ref>
